Impeachment hearings @realDonaldTrump Adam Schiff opened his remarks with these dramatic words: "When a man unprincipled in private life [and] desperate in his fortune, bold in his temper . . . despotic in his ordinary demeanor—known to have scoffed in private at the principles

of liberty—when such a man is seen to mount the hobby horse of popularity. . . it may justly be suspected that his object is to throw things into confusion." The words describe Trump perfectly. Only after delivering them did Schiff reveal that they were written by Alexander

Hamilton to George Washington, warning against public sentiment to convert our young republic into “that of a monarchy.” Hamilton saw a possible threat to democracy arising from a man who was immoral, intemperate, financially desperate, and despotic. Schiff used Hamilton’s words
